## Thread.Abort Migration to .NET 8

Your code has three APIs that **don't work** in .NET 6+:

| API | .NET 8 Behavior |
|-----|-----------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never thrown by the runtime |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

### Pattern Classification

| Location | Pattern | Replacement |
|----------|---------|-------------|
| `ProcessLoop()` while loop | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control-flow cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Check `IsCancellationRequested`, continue loop |
| `Stop()` → `Thread.Abort()` | Force-kill thread | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `GetNextItem()` (blocks) | Blocking call interruption | Must accept `CancellationToken` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed. The loop condition will exit naturally.
                // If you want to drain remaining items instead of stopping
                // immediately, you could 'continue' here with a secondary check.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals the token — cooperative, not forcible

        // Give the thread time to finish its current work item
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
        // If the thread is still alive after Join, it means GetNextItem or
        // ProcessItem isn't responding to cancellation. See pitfalls below.
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

### Critical: `GetNextItem` Must Cooperate

The comment says `GetNextItem()` "may block." This is the **#1 pitfall** — cancelling a token does nothing if the blocking call ignores it. You must update it:

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework) — Thread.Abort would inject an exception here
private object GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks indefinitely
}

// AFTER (.NET 8) — responds to cancellation
private object GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException when cancelled
}
```

If `GetNextItem` does synchronous I/O (e.g., `socket.Receive`), replace it with async I/O or use `token.WaitHandle` for polling:

```csharp
// Replacing a blocking wait with a cancellable one
private object GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!_dataAvailable.WaitOne(500))     // poll every 500ms
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return DequeueItem();
}
```

### Key Pitfalls for This Migration

| Pitfall | Why It Matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **`GetNextItem` still blocks ignoring the token** | Cancellation will stall. The thread never wakes up. `Join(2000)` expires and you have a zombie thread. |
| **`ProcessItem` runs for minutes without checking** | Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints inside `ProcessItem` to keep cancellation responsive. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers and callbacks. Always wrap in `IDisposable` or `using`. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException` broadly** | The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not unrelated ones. |
| **Removing rollback logic when deleting the catch** | The original `ThreadAbortException` catch did `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` — this **must** be preserved in the new `OperationCanceledException` catch. |

### What Changed and Why

```
Thread.Abort()           →  CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()
                             (cooperative signal, not forced injection)

ThreadAbortException     →  OperationCanceledException
                             (thrown explicitly by token-aware APIs)

Thread.ResetAbort()      →  simply continue the loop
                             (no forced exception to suppress)

Thread.Sleep(2000)       →  Thread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2))
                             (actually waits for the thread, not arbitrary delay)

volatile bool _running   →  CancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested
                             (single mechanism instead of bool + Abort)
```

The fundamental shift: .NET Framework could **forcibly inject** an exception into any thread at any point. .NET 8 requires the thread's code to **voluntarily check** for cancellation. Every blocking call in the chain must accept and respect the `CancellationToken`.
